******
[2]
Date: Tue 4 Aug 2020
From: EpiCore Global Surveillance Project member [edited]


The new bunyavirus has infected at least 37 individuals in Jiangsu, and it seems to be at risk of spreading from person to person. Main symptoms are high fever, cough fatigue, and thrombocytopenia. The so-called "new bunyavirus" is not a new virus strain that has just been discovered. It was isolated already in 2011 and defined as belonging to _Bunyaviridae_ and the _Phlebovirus_ genus.

The recent patient reported by media suffered from severe fever with thrombocytopenia syndrome (SFTS): Clinical manifestations of SFTS are nonspecific and include mainly fever, peripheral blood thrombocytopenia, leukopenia, and gastrointestinal discomfort. In severe cases, multiple organ failure may occur. This has been described in this latest patient. For this reason, the involved hospital (Jiangsu Provincial People's Hospital) has organized multidisciplinary consultations involving the Emergency Medicine Center, the Department of Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine, the Department of Infectious Diseases, and the ICU. It was finally agreed that the patient was infected with "new bunyavirus" and had "secondary inflammatory factors."

Health authority representatives recently said in radio/TV local interviews that "usually, tick bites can cause skin inflammatory allergic reactions, which can be cured by correct treatment and symptomatic treatment; however, as ticks are also vectors of many pathogens, they cause infectious diseases."

The question is, can the new bunyavirus spread from person to person? The Ministry of Health's (MoH) "Fever with Thrombocytopenia Syndrome Prevention Guide" (2010) mentions that during the acute stage patients may be contagious (1).

During 2012, a person in Shandong (China) died of the new bunyavirus and 5 more people were infected; these included one ICU doctor, one consulting doctor, 2 sons of the patient, and one instrument staff in the funeral home (2).

The 2010 MoH document states that case management should be strengthened to reduce the risk of transmission. Under normal circumstances, there is no need to isolate the patient: Blood, secretions, excrement, contaminated environment and objects of the patient can be disinfected by high temperature, high pressure, and chlorine-containing disinfectants. However, in case of critical patients, for example, patients bleeding (e.g., hemoptysis, hematemesis), the medical staff and other personnel should strengthen personal protection and avoid direct contact with the patient.

The new bunyavirus is mainly transmitted via ticks that are active in China in the affected areas (hills, forests, bushes, open pastures, grasslands, mountains, etc.) between April and October. Health authorities have reminded the population to avoid sitting and lying in grass, woods and other places for a long time and when visiting these areas to wear long-sleeved clothes, no sandals, tie trouser legs tucked into socks and wear light-colored clothes. Parents should make sure their children do not play in wild grass/bushes. In case a person is bitten, they should go to the closest hospital to remove the tick in time. Do not remove it yourself. In case of symptoms after being bitten by a tick, the person should seek medical care as soon as possible and avoid close contact with others. Pets may also be affected: After returning home from a visit in such areas, people should check them for ticks.

References
1. Ministry of Health of the People's Republic of China. Guidelines for the prevention and treatment of fever with thrombocytopenia syndrome (2010 edition). Chinese J Clin Infect Dis. 2011; 04(4): 193-4. doi: 10.3760/cma.j.issn.1674-2397.2011.04.001
2. Gai Z, Liang M, Zhang Y, et al. Person-to-person transmission of severe fever with thrombocytopenia syndrome bunyavirus through blood contact. Clin Infect Dis. 2011; 54(2): 249-52.


