[ProMED-mail thanks the EpiCore contributor who contributed the 2nd report.

As noted in earlier ProMED posts, SFTS is a serious disease and of significant public health concern. Although SFTS virus infections may be serious with case fatality rates reported to range from 1%-50%, there is evidence for subclinical or mild infections as well. There is also some evidence for person-to-person direct transmission of the virus. Nevertheless, the virus is doubtless endemic in China and other countries in Asia.

An earlier report from China reported a case of a subclinical, secondary infection that was most likely caused by person-to-person transmission of the virus from an infected family member with a fatal case of SFTS (see Severe fever w/ thrombocytopenia syndrome - China, South Korea 20140705.2589725). The investigators found an overall SFTSV seroprevalence of 7.2% among 986 healthy persons who reported no symptoms associated with SFTS in Zhejiang Province, China. Because the seropositive participants in that study did not have contact with persons with diagnosed cases of SFTS, their infections most likely occurred through natural exposure. From this, it was concluded that SFTSV infections are widespread in rural areas of Zhejiang Province, and only a small percentage of the infections result in clinical disease.

The longhorn tick (_Haemaphysalis longicornis_) is the virus vector. There is no vaccine, and avoidance of tick bites is the only currently available preventive measure. Images of this tick can be seen at http://www.lowchensaustralia.com/pests/paralysis-tick/haemaphysalis-longicornis-description.htm. - Mod.TY

